{"title": "Unbiased Collaborative Filtering with Fair Sampling", "domain": "IR_REC", "seeds": [{"problem": "Implicit-feedback recommender models trained with classic point-wise or pair-wise losses inherit popularity bias because observed interactions conflate true relevance with exposure propensities of active users and popular items.", "method": "Introduce Fair Sampling (FS), a sampling-level training scheme that, for every training instance, constructs supplementary samples so each user and each item are equally likely to appear as both positive and negative. Two variants are provided: FS-Point for point-wise losses and FS-Pair for pair-wise losses. FS-Point augments each (u,i,y) with complementary user–item samples that flip labels to balance appearances; FS-Pair augments each positive–negative pair (u,i;j) with a crossed pair (ũ,j,i) under non-interaction constraints. This cancels the optimization of user/item propensity factors in the loss and removes the need to estimate propensity scores, thereby mitigating popularity bias."}, {"problem": "Existing IPS-based debiasing relies on estimating propensity scores, which is difficult in practice and can introduce high variance or residual bias; a principled alternative is needed that targets the source of bias in the objectives themselves.", "method": "Provide a theoretical analysis that decomposes exposure probability into user propensity, item propensity, and relevance, then shows classic point-wise and pair-wise objectives implicitly optimize propensity terms (e.g., ln φ_u and ln φ_i), biasing models toward popular items. Prove that the FS constructions (FS-Point and FS-Pair) offset these propensity terms in the optimization—so only the relevance component is optimized—achieving unbiased learning without propensity estimation."}]}
